<img src="https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/578b0b1f8bfe3ec3982509a62b783bd6?s=32&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g">			<cite><a href="http://westernsemico.com">Adam Joseph</a></cite> <span>says:</span>		</div>
<div>
<a href="https://www.bunniestudios.com/blog/?p=6937#comment-2621968">March 10, 2024 at 5:40 am</a>		</div>
<p>Hey cool!  So glad to see NLNet funding this kind of work!</p>
<p>&gt; the backside finish of the 130nm chip is a mirror polish</p>
<p>Backside power delivery is now used on essentially all recent high-end CPUs and GPUs.  Do backside power TSVs impede IRIS?</p>
<p>&gt; IRIS can place an upper bound on gate count to within a couple dozen extra flip flops.</p>
<p>Most commercial designs have large “NAND oceans” — spare gates with their inputs tied off.  This allows the manufacturer to fix simple bugs with only two or three mask changes — i.e. just enough metal changes to wire up the bugfix using those spare NAND gates and splice it in.  These NAND oceans are totally normal; all commercial chips have them.  Sometimes they’re even inserted automatically by the fill generator!</p>
<p>Would IRIS detect a malicious use of spare gates?</p>
<p>&gt; 130nm chip fabricated using the SKY130A open PDK</p>
<p>Are they accepting bookings (paid if necessary) for designs that don’t use the Caravel “Management Engine” padframe/wrapper (which has its own CPU and firmware)?  Last time I checked the user’s circuit had no access to the outside world except through the management engine, which was pretty disappointing.  I had a very hard time getting any clarity from them on this issue.</p>
<p>&gt; it will become more open within the next decade if the world continues on a “business as usual” scenario where technology continues to race down the commodification curve</p>
<p>I sure hope so, but there was a big “secrecy-level” discontinuity when OPC was introduced at 90nm.  Oftentimes the OPC techniques were not developed by the fabs, but were rather licensed from third party companies — especially in the early OPC nodes when the technique was new and very few research groups could get it to work reliably.  You can reverse engineer quite a lot about the OPC process from the physical design rules, which include lists of “forbidden shapes”.  So, in many cases the fabs can’t make design rule openness decisions on their own — they’re subject to NDAs with the companies that developed the OPC techniques they’ve licensed.  The OPC problem was why MOSIS never tried to push their fab-independent SCMOS design rules past 180nm.</p>
<p>Little-known fact: at 180nm you can, with very few exceptions, simply double or quadruple the size of an entire design (i.e. draw the gates 360nm wide, place 2×2 via arrays where each via would have been, etc).  Everything will run slower and you’ll have to revalidate timing of course.  But if you *wanted* to fab a secure element with gates large enough to IRIS-image directly, in exchange for a big performance hit… that’s probably possible with current trailing-node commercial fabs.  Anything too small to resolve would be treated as an immediate red flag.</p>
<div><a href="https://www.bunniestudios.com/blog/?p=6937&amp;replytocom=2621968#respond" data-commentid="2621968" data-postid="6937" data-belowelement="div-comment-2621968" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Adam Joseph" aria-label="Reply to Adam Joseph">Reply</a></div>
