<img src="https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/80798e90e0ad7f00bd9aa22d2638f82e?s=32&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g">			<cite>bunnie</cite> <span>says:</span>		</div>
<div>
<a href="https://www.bunniestudios.com/blog/?p=6937#comment-2622063">March 10, 2024 at 2:23 pm</a>		</div>
<p>&gt; Backside power delivery is now used on essentially all recent high-end CPUs and GPUs. Do backside power TSVs impede IRIS?</p>
<p>Yes, backside metallization would interfere with IRIS. So, you can’t use IRIS on chips with backside power delivery. Aside from X-ray Ptychography, I can’t think of any reliable way to ascertain if the most advanced chips have been built correctly, which is why I am generally assuming any security-first system would offload root keys and bulk cryptography to an external device that is inspectable. The good news is it seems feasible to build some  kind of PCIe-attached device with good security properties and enough performance to keep up with modern (e.g. 10Gbps) data rates in older, more inspectable nodes.</p>
<p>&gt; Most commercial designs have large “NAND oceans” — spare gates with their inputs tied off. This allows the manufacturer to fix simple bugs with only two or three mask changes — i.e. just enough metal changes to wire up the bugfix using those spare NAND gates and splice it in. These NAND oceans are totally normal; all commercial chips have them. Sometimes they’re even inserted automatically by the fill generator!</p>
<p>&gt; Would IRIS detect a malicious use of spare gates?</p>
<p>The good news is that other researchers have already addressed this issue. The basic idea is that you disallow fully unconnected spare gates — the spare gates are wired into the scan chain. Thus when a gate is spared out, you’ll see that in the test vectors.</p>
<p>For more reading, have a browse through <a href="https://dblp.org/pid/t/MohammadTehranipoor.html">Mark Tehranipoor’s bibliography</a>. His research group has thought a lot about the spare gates problem and scan chains. Generally, I would assume any designer of a chip that plans to enlist IRIS inspection would also at a minimum have already deployed most of the best practices informed by his research. I see IRIS as complimentary to his body of work, and not as replacement or substitution for good design practices. Same applies to questions about things like dopant tampering, etc. There is a canon of hardening techniques that needs to be applied at the circuit level, IRIS does not excuse a designer to be sloppy.</p>
<p>The main contribution of IRIS is that it breaks the epistemic circularity problem of relying on a circuit to self-report its integrity. You can think of it as a second-factor authentication of a primary factor that is a circuit self-test. Just as in MFA, the primary factor still needs to be correctly implemented (e.g. deploying 2FA doesn’t mean it’s OK to start using weak passwords and store password plaintexts in your database); and just as in MFA you can’t rely on the primary factor only because you can’t necessarily trust the user’s browser or phone to not be rooted. You also can’t just throw away the primary factor and just rely on the second factor…because you’re back to a single factor.</p>
<p>&gt; 130nm chip fabricated using the SKY130A open PDK</p>
<p>&gt; Are they accepting bookings (paid if necessary) for designs that don’t use the Caravel “Management Engine” padframe/wrapper (which has its own CPU and firmware)? Last time I checked the user’s circuit had no access to the outside world except through the management engine, which was pretty disappointing. I had a very hard time getting any clarity from them on this issue.</p>
<p>I can’t answer for efabless, but if you’re willing to pay, I think they’re willing to cut a deal. My impression is that the caravel harness is provided as training wheels for folks who have never done an ASIC before, because problems in pad rings, ESD, management interfaces, etc. are things that most people have zero interest in but are easy ways to waste a tape out. But, if it’s your money, I bet they’ll be happy to take it so long as you’re committed to paying for whatever comes out. There’s some other nuance like caravel ensuring you’re  DRC clean, but from the questions you’re asking it sounds like you’d already be aware of those rules, and not hopping up and down mad when a foundry says no to a design you paid for that will literally fall apart and litter their production equipment with metal slivers.</p>
<p>&gt; I sure hope so, but there was a big “secrecy-level” discontinuity when OPC was introduced at 90nm. Oftentimes the OPC techniques were not developed by the fabs, but were rather licensed from third party companies — especially in the early OPC nodes when the technique was new and very few research groups could get it to work reliably. You can reverse engineer quite a lot about the OPC process from the physical design rules, which include lists of “forbidden shapes”. So, in many cases the fabs can’t make design rule openness decisions on their own — they’re subject to NDAs with the companies that developed the OPC techniques they’ve licensed. The OPC problem was why MOSIS never tried to push their fab-independent SCMOS design rules past 180nm.</p>
<p>I know people who are explicitly working to overcome the mask making monopoly. They aren’t doing this out of altruism or some principled argument about security — there’s money to be made, and a lot of it — if you can get more designers taping out chips in nodes that are smaller than 130nm but larger than 14nm. As I mentioned in the post, the best value-per-transistor node is around 22 or 28nm, and there’s a lot of production volume being built around it. Every nation-state interested in self-sovereign foundries would be advised to build a fab producing at this node. Aside from some specialty HV or MEMs processes, fabs also want to cut down on the number of legacy lines they have to operate, and migrate all their customers to the most economical node — but who is going to pay for those masks? The silicon business is a story of boom-and-bust cycles. My bet is that in a couple of “business as usual” economic cycles, all those 2x nm fabs are going to be fully depreciated, and the foundries will be scrambling for ways to get more wafer starts — and if its a choice between going out of business or open design rules, they’ll probably pick the latter. Or maybe they just get government grants and do none of the above, who knows. It did take us over 500 years to go from Gutenburg to desktop publishing, after all. But, as long as the world doesn’t implode I think the economics align with open design rules at the “value” process nodes.</p>
<p>&gt; Little-known fact: at 180nm you can, with very few exceptions, simply double or quadruple the size of an entire design (i.e. draw the gates 360nm wide, place 2×2 via arrays where each via would have been, etc). Everything will run slower and you’ll have to revalidate timing of course. But if you *wanted* to fab a secure element with gates large enough to IRIS-image directly, in exchange for a big performance hit… that’s probably possible with current trailing-node commercial fabs. Anything too small to resolve would be treated as an immediate red flag.</p>
<p>Good point, “scalable” CMOS rules can scale in both directions! I think you would still want to employ scan chains because IRIS can’t see the upper metal layers. With larger standard cells, you could get a very high confidence gate count, but the inter-gate wiring is still difficult to resolve. Plus, a would-be interloper isn’t bound to use your larger standard cells — they would still be free to put a handful of minimum-sized logic cells on the mask, and the foundry will happily fabricate them. So IRIS would still probably have to flag anything that’s out of place which *could* be a logic cell in the target process node, even if the designer voluntarily adopts a larger scaling rule.</p>
