<div><a href="https://www.bunniestudios.com/blog/?p=6937&amp;replytocom=2622107#respond" data-commentid="2622107" data-postid="6937" data-belowelement="div-comment-2622107" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to 红外辐射在位硅验证项目更新 - 偏执的码农" aria-label="Reply to 红外辐射在位硅验证项目更新 - 偏执的码农">Reply</a></div>
</li>
<li>
<div>
<img src="https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/578b0b1f8bfe3ec3982509a62b783bd6?s=32&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g">			<cite><a href="http://westernsemico.com">Adam Joseph</a></cite> <span>says:</span>		</div>
<div>
<a href="https://www.bunniestudios.com/blog/?p=6937#comment-2622333">March 11, 2024 at 2:35 pm</a>		</div>
<p>Thanks for the detailed reply!  Super clever to put the spare gates into the scan chain so they aren’t actually spare!  What a great idea.  Will definitely read up on that line of research.</p>
<p>&gt; &gt; I had a very hard time getting any clarity from them on this issue.</p>
<p>&gt; I can’t answer for efabless, but if you’re willing to pay, I think they’re willing to cut a deal. </p>
<p>I did in fact offer to pay full price (for an MPW seat, not an entire maskset), do GDS handoff (the GDS for the foundry-provided pad/ring/esd cells are in the open PDK), and accept full responsibility for getting back a doorstop … and still couldn’t get a clear reply out of them.</p>
<p>I got the impression that they see Caravel as being their actual product — so people who don’t want it are sort of cutting them out of the deal, in a sense.  So the reluctance to encourage that kind of thing is understandable.  Just getting the SK130 rules out from under NDA was a big victory; they’ve done enough good deeds for one company.</p>
<p>&gt; a would-be interloper isn’t bound to use your larger standard cells — they would still be free to put a handful of minimum-sized logic cells on the mask</p>
<p>You can cover all of the unused areas with obstruction patterns on the Metal-1 layer (which I assume is most of what IRIS shows… the tungsten diffusion/poly contacts are way too small).  As long as the interloper can’t use Metal-1, they can’t connect anything to the gates of those below-minimum-sized cells.</p>
<p>&gt; the best value-per-transistor node is around 22 or 28nm</p>
<p>Yes, absolutely.  That last planar generation will be around for a very, very long time to come and represents the final result of decades of optimization.</p>
<p>&gt; I know people who are explicitly working to overcome the mask making monopoly.  …  as long as the world doesn’t implode I think the economics align with open design rules at the “value” process nodes.</p>
<p>I sure hope so.  And I hope you’ll post here about any progress in that area!</p>
